# Temperature Data Logger

Another hardware project, but this time one that I regularly still use, is a digital thermometer. 

It's actually quite a simple set up, based around a [DS18B20](https://datasheets.maximintegrated.com/en/ds/DS18B20.pdf) one wire bus temperature sensor.

## Motivation
One summer, it was hot. Really hot. The days were regularly getting over 30&deg;c, and, working in an attic office, it was like being in an oven. I wanted to get a log of the temperature over the course of the day, so that I could share it with facilities and the office managers, to try and make an argument that these were not acceptable working conditions.

So naturally, I turned to hardware to help me out.

## Hardware

Essentially, I followed two guides from Raspberry Pi:
- One for [setting up a thermometer](https://tutorials-raspberrypi.com/raspberry-pi-temperature-sensor-1wire-ds18b20/)
- One for [adding a 16x2 or 20x4 Character LCD display](https://tutorials-raspberrypi.com/raspberry-pi-lcd-display-16x2-characters-display-hd44780/)

I also used a custom printed circuit board to mount everything together in a nice little package.

![thermometer](data:image/png;base64,)

## Circuits
The Circuit for this project wasn't too fancy. It is based on a combination of two guides from Raspberry PI.

![thermometer](https://tutorials-raspberrypi.com/wp-content/uploads/Raspberry-Pi-Temperature-Sensor-DS18B20-1-Wire-Setup-457x500.png).

The first circuit is for the thermometer, and essentially connects to the 1 wire bus pins on the pi.

![display](https://tutorials-raspberrypi.de/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/lcd_Steckplatine-329x300.png)

The second circuit is for the display. In my circuit, I modified the potentiometer that controls the backlight of the display to be three discreet resistors with fixed values, and used a jumper to switch between them.

## Software
Finally, I tied it all together with a few nifty bash scripts:
1. A script that gathers the data from the thermometer and writes it to a CSV file for the current day
2. A script that puts the data into a graph for the day
3. A script that would email the graph to myself/my office managers.

The scripts are all in [GitHub](https://github.com/dlpb/pi-temperature-monitor), but I haven't changed them since I wrote them.

It was a bit of fun learning about [GNUPlot](http://www.gnuplot.info/), and [Sendmail](https://www.computerhope.com/unix/usendmai.htm); and led to some fancy graphs!

## Conclusions
This was an interesting, and ultimately quite useful, project. As a result of having data to back us up, our office managers were able to install new air conditioning systems to help keep the office cooler.

Just as interesting, though not so useful, was what the data revealed. You could spot office working patterns from the data, like when everyone arrived, when everyone took lunch, etc. You could even tell when (large numbers of) people were on holiday by comparing different day's data.

While I don't work in that office now, I do still use the device. It sits on my desk at home, and reports the current temperature in my home office. Now, I have no one to complain to except myself, but it's still fun to see.
